reviewText: This is one of my favorite movies.  Not because of its ability to touch the human spirit, or inspire to greatness, or...well, you get the idea.  It's because it's AWESOME.  Gore, lesbian scenes, too much jungle vampire hotness to handle.  Not to mention a thoroughly amazing plot (and by amazing, I mean a plot that is ridiculously outlandish and yet amazingly is well put together enough to stay interesting).  You will never be bored.  You will never regret this movie.  The fact that you are here looking at this review tells me you are the kind of person that WILL like this movie.

reviewText: I'm not going to lie, I didn't go into "Skin Eating Jungle Vampires" hoping that it had simply been overlooked for Academy Award consideration (circa 2002) for political reasons.  No.  Assembled by cult underground figure Mr. Creepo, I hoped that this B-movie would aspire to some cleverness, some sexiness, and some genuine bad movie magic!  Within one minute, the film's ridiculous opening sequence almost made me cut my losses and turn this sucker off.  A Betty Page wannabe is attacked by a group of tribal appearing women.  With cougar sounds overlaying the soundtrack, they pounce on their prey threateningly and then begin to playfully spank her and fondle her--it's so patently nonsensical, several of the "actresses" are conspicuously seen giggling throughout the scene.  Awful, awful, awful.  But then, after a sci-fi twist, the main story launches when the attack victim's sister has a premonition that something nefarious has befallen her sibling.  I stuck with the uneven film--which is alternately ludicrous, hilarious, and inept--and darned if I didn't end up having some affection for this sexploitation oddity.First, the title is a complete misnomer.  Looking for skin eating?  Not here.  But if you like raw meat being smeared onto nude or near nude women, this is a bonanza!  Looking for vampiric action?  Not hardly.  At best, assuming they didn't waste all their food squeezing it seductively, the girls might be considered cannibals.  And what's more erotic than two women consensually engaging in the exchange of raw liver fluids and intestinal matter?  Turns out, the women are from another planet (whose name won't pass review censors--but where tattoos and tongue piercing rule!) trapped with their god in a Costa Rican volcano.  To escape, they must marry up their supreme being to a human sacrifice and then they will be free to devour the world.Our frantic sister hops a plane to Costa Rica, and is in such a frenzy to begin her life or death quest that she spends the day luxuriating at the beach.  Mr. Creepo, in cahoots with the cannibalistic tribe, was responsible for choosing the first victim and is now drawn to this new heroine as well.  Creepo is the film's most underutilized element.  In a hilarious monologue, he ogles this chick and then plants a rubber snake in her room.  Had Mr. Creepo played a more prominent role, I suspect this might have been genuine bad movie genius.  We follow the sister through the jungle where the reunion is only the first part of the epic finale.The over-the-top finale is stunningly fantastic--so laughably ridiculous and sublime.  I absolutely loved it!  (I especially liked that the secluded vampires had a hand crank meat grinder and their leader waved around rainbow feather dusters!)  However, this five star ending failed to make up for some of the film's more painful moments which had begun as one star drudgery.  I'll even things out at 3 stars (mind you, that is still on the bad movie scale)--and encourage anyone who enjoys this sort of thing to give this a try.  If it doesn't sound appealing, stay far far away.  KGHarris, 4/11.
summary: Sapphic Sexploitation--A Mr. Creepo Cheapo That Borders On Brilliant Badness
